</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,152,1144]" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">
This African genus comprises a somewhat heterogeneous collection of chameleons which encompasses at least four species complexes (
<emphasis box="[513,957,887,912]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName box="[513,588,887,912]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Trioceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="affinis">affinis</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName authority="Laurenti, 1768" authorityName="Laurenti" authorityYear="1768" box="[596,702,887,912]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Chameleo" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cristatus">cristatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[715,851,887,912]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Trioceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bitaeniatus">bitaeniatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[864,957,887,912]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Chamaeleo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="werneri">werneri</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
– 
<bibRefCitation author="Hillenius" box="[988,1169,886,912]" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" refString="Hillenius, D. (1959) The differentiation within the genus Chamaeleo Laurenti 1768. Beaufortia, 8 (89), 1 - 92." type="journal article" year="1959">
Hillenius 
<number box="[1106,1169,886,912]" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" value="1959.0">1959</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Klaver" box="[1182,1333,886,912]" pageId="10" pageNumber="68" refString="Klaver, C. J. J. (1981) Lung morphology in the Chamaeleonidae (Sauria) and its bearing on phylogeny, systematics and zoogeography. Zeitschriftfuer zoologishe Systematik Evolutionsforsch, 19, 36 - 58." type="journal article" year="1981">
Klaver 
<number box="[1271,1333,886,912]" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Koreny" pageId="10" pageNumber="68" refString="Koreny, L. (2006) Phylogeny of East-African chameleons. MSc Thesis, Faculty of Biological Sciences, University of South Bohemia in Ceske Budejovice, April 2006." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Koreny 
<number box="[151,212,925,951]" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) which are currently loosely named “groups” as well as a single species that does not fit into any of the other groups viz: 
<emphasis box="[368,493,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1865" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1865" box="[368,489,964,989]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Ensirostris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melleri">T. melleri</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Three of the five sub-groups within this genus have probably independently developed a viviparous reproductive strategy (
<emphasis box="[692,910,1002,1027]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName box="[692,768,1002,1027]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Trioceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="affinis">affinis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[780,910,1002,1027]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Trioceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bitaeniatus">bitaeniatus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[966,1057,1002,1027]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Chamaeleo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="werneri">
<emphasis box="[966,1057,1002,1027]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">werneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups), whilst the fourth group (
<taxonomicName authority="Laurenti, 1768" authorityName="Laurenti" authorityYear="1768" box="[161,261,1041,1066]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Chameleo" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cristatus">
<emphasis box="[161,261,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">cristatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1865" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1865" box="[328,438,1041,1066]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" genus="Ensirostris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melleri">
<emphasis box="[328,438,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">T. melleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have retained oviparous modes of reproduction. The viviparous groups have a dense melanotic infiltration of the parietal pigmentation – a condition usually associated with viviparity in the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,350,1118,1144]" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Chamaeleonidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
